<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-152-216  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 152 216.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computers in Banking  Feb 1990 v7 n2 p36(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>New tools help large banks manage mass storage squeeze. (includesa related article on alternative media storage devices)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hellauer, Brian.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Banks are transaction intensive organizations, and the need tomaintain records means those records must be stored somewhere.andP;  Asa result banks are finding it difficult to keep up with theirstorage needs.andP;  Although disk storage technology is improvingconstantly, it is an electro-mechanical media, meaning thattechnical refinements come gradually.andP;  IBM's new 3390 directaccess storage drive (DASD) offers 22.7 gigabytes of storage,triple the capacity of the 3380, in a unit that is one-third thesize.andP;  A method for maximizing DASD efficiency is to transfer datato tape storage as quickly as possible.andP;  Tape storage is muchcheaper than disk storage, and the advent of automatic 'silos'that transfer the data means lower personnel requirements.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Disk StorageBankingStorage MediaTape StorageDirect Access Storage DevicesStorage Density.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>